# Docker vs Kubernetes

| Feature | Docker | Kubernetes |
|------|------|------|
| Platform Type | Containerization Platform | Container Orchestration Platform |
| Purpose | Create and run containers | Manage containers |
| Scaling | Manual | Automatic |
| Load Balancing | Limited | Built-in |
| Self Healing | Not Available | Available |

---

# Docker

Docker is used for **creating containers**.

It packages applications into **Docker images**.

Example workflow:

```
Application Code
      |
      v
Dockerfile
      |
      v
Docker Image
      |
      v
Docker Container
```

A **container** is simply a **running instance of a Docker image**.

Docker ensures applications run consistently across environments.

---

# Kubernetes

Kubernetes is responsible for **managing containers across servers**.

Kubernetes performs tasks such as:

```
Deploy Containers
Scale Containers
Restart Failed Containers
Distribute Traffic
Monitor Application Health
```

Example structure:

```
Users
  |
  v
Load Balancer
  |
  v
Kubernetes Cluster
  |
  |---- Container1
  |---- Container2
  |---- Container3
  |---- Container4
```

Kubernetes ensures containers are always **running and available**.

